1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O {It's strange to think that this
natural move was once a sideline!} ({The other main options are} 4... c5) ({and
} 4... b6 {(see games in the archives)}) ({while} 4... d5 {transposes to the
Ragozin.}) 5. Bg5 c5 6. Rc1 (6. e3 {is the alternative, most recently examined
in Vachier Lagrave,M-So,W/Leuven 2018.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 cxd4 (7... g5 $6 {
is premature - see the notes to Bacrot,E-Inkiov,V/Haguenau 2013.}) 8. Nxd4 d5
$1 (8... Nc6 9. e3 b6 10. Ndb5 $1 {gives White as edge, as we saw in Aronian,
L-Caruana,F/ Leuven 2016.}) 9. cxd5 (9. e3 e5 $1 10. Nf3 d4 $1 {was some
excellent prep by Black - see the notes to Eduoard,R-Nakamura,H/ Caleta 2017.})
9... g5 $1 {As is typical in many lines of the Nimzo, Black needs to
prioritise activity and accept weaknesses to do so.} 10. Bg3 Qxd5 11. e3 Qxa2
$5 ({So far we've been following Gelfand,B-Inarkiev,E/Magas 2016, in which
Black played} 11... Ne4 {- see the notes to that game also for earlier
possibilities.}) 12. Bd3 $1 {The first new move, and a challenging one for
Black to face.} ({Previously} 12. Qc2 {had been tried. For example,} Nd5 13. h4
Nxc3 14. hxg5 $5 (14. bxc3 Qxc2 15. Rxc2 Be7 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Be5 f6 18. Bxb8
Rxb8 19. Bc4 b5 20. Bxe6+ Bxe6 21. Nxe6 Rfc8 $11) 14... Na4+ 15. Kd1 Qxb2 16.
Qxb2 Nxb2+ 17. Kc2 Be7 18. Kxb2 Bxg5 19. Be5 Nd7 20. Bd6 Rd8 21. f4 Bf6 22. Bc7
Re8 23. Rxh6 e5 24. Nf5 exf4+ 25. Ka3 Be5 26. exf4 Bxc7 27. Rxc7 Nb6 28. Rh5 {
1/2-1/2 Cavajda,I-Peuraniemi,P/ICCF email 2012.}) 12... Qxb2 13. O-O $1 Bxc3
14. Rc2 Qb4 15. Nb5 e5 16. Rxc3 Nc6 {Black has had to play a string of 'only
moves' and must remain very careful in the face of White's pressure. The
computer believes Black is fine, but this is of minimal comfort when playing
Black's position over the board!} 17. f4 $1 (17. Rxc6 bxc6 18. Bxe5 Qg4 $1 19.
Nc7 Qxd1 20. Rxd1 Nd7 $15) 17... Bg4 (17... gxf4 {can be met by} 18. Bh4 $5)
18. Qc2 exf4 (18... Nd5 $5) 19. exf4 Rac8 (19... Nh5 $5) 20. Bc4 (20. fxg5 $5
Nd4 21. Qf2 $1 Ne4 $1 (21... Rxc3 22. Qxf6 $18) 22. Bxe4 Ne2+ 23. Kh1 Nxc3 24.
Nxc3 Qxc3 25. gxh6 {and the engines slightly prefer White's attacking chances
to Black's extra material.}) 20... Qc5+ 21. Kh1 Qf5 $1 22. Bd3 Qd7 23. fxg5 Nb4
$1 24. Qf2 Nxd3 25. Qxf6 Qxb5 26. gxh6 Nf2+ 27. Rxf2 ({White could have
considered} 27. Qxf2 $5 Rxc3 28. Qf6 Qxf1+ 29. Qxf1 Rc6 30. h3) 27... Qb1+ 28.
Rf1 Qg6 29. Rxc8 Rxc8 30. Qe7 Be6 31. Qxb7 Qxh6 32. Qxa7 Rc1 $1 {Extremely
accurate defence in a difficult position from Ding Liren. Black is over the
worst and a draw is soon in sight.} 33. Rg1 Rxg1+ 34. Qxg1 Bd5 35. Qd1 Qe6 36.
Qd2 Qf5 37. Kg1 Qb1+ 38. Be1 Qb6+ 39. Kh1 Qf6 40. h3 Qf5 41. Kh2 f6 42. Bf2 Kf7
43. Bd4 Ke6 44. Qe3+ Qe4 45. Qf2 Qf5 46. Qg3 Qe4 47. Bc3 Kf5 48. Qf2+ Qf4+ $1
49. Qxf4+ Kxf4 50. Bxf6 Kf5 51. Bc3 Kg6 52. g4 Be6 53. Kg3 Bd7 54. h4 Be6 55.
h5+ Kh7 56. Kf4 Bd7 57. g5 Be8 {The perfect defensive formation against the
connected pawns in an opposite-coloured bishop ending.} 58. Kg4 Bf7 59. g6+
Bxg6 60. hxg6+ Kxg6 {This looks like a good practical line for White. Black is
a pawn or two ahead but has to defence with computer-like accuracy.} 1/2-1/2

